{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"22de3942-dea1-42cf-abc8-a16b2e1de709","content":"Here's the evaluation performance analysis for `EvalHeavy.csproj`:\n\n## Issues Found\n\n### 1. File I/O Property Function (High Impact)\n**Line 13:** `$([System.IO.File]::ReadAllText('build-notes.txt'))`\n\nThis performs disk I/O during evaluation — one of the most expensive operations in this phase. It runs on every single evaluation (design-time builds, restores, etc.). **Fix:** Read the file in a target at execution time, or use a build task.\n\n### 2. Overly Broad Glob Pattern (Medium Impact)\n**Line 9:** `<AdditionalFiles Include=\"**\\*.*\" ...>`\n\nThe `**\\*.*` glob walks the entire directory tree during evaluation. As the project grows (or if `node_modules`/large folders appear), this becomes a bottleneck. **Fix:** Narrow the glob to specific extensions or directories, or add large directories to `DefaultItemExcludes`.\n\n### 3. Chained Import Depth (Low Impact)\n`level1.props → level2.props → level3.props` creates a 3-level deep import chain. While only 3 levels here, this pattern scales poorly. Each import adds evaluation overhead. **Fix:** Flatten imports where possible, or consolidate into a single `.props` file.\n\n---\n\n**Summary:** The file I/O property function and broad glob are the primary concerns. The import chain is minor at this depth but worth watching.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"b81399b7-85f9-41be-b99b-aa8a13aafd1c","outputTokens":338,"requestId":"EC10:1E6FAE:864D6E:A64B39:6A013222"},"id":"db4bf5c8-8e1e-45f6-aabf-a1b30c904dd2","timestamp":"2026-05-11T01:34:35.401Z","parentId":"4b9e1a01-aa22-40fd-a3ad-59f4b39d0272"}
